@EndNode

@Node "Inst" "Installation"

  @{b}Installation instructions@{ub}

    Nothing to it really, copy this entire drawer to Pagestream:scripts/
    and assign the scripts to whatever function keys you fancy.

    Of course, should you decide to install the scripts elsewhere,
    you will have to change all search paths in the scripts accordingly.

    This is simply arexx stuff, so loading the database into a trio
    of compound variables, at startup, takes quite a bit of time.
    Therefore there are four scripts:

	@{fg shine}        imeserver.rexx@{fg text}  This is the main script, which loads the
                                database and then just sits there, waiting 
                                for requests from the smaller input scripts.

	@{fg shine}   kill-imeserver.rexx@{fg text}  Shuts down the IME Server, 
                                rexxecute this when you're done.

	@{fg shine}      find-pinyin.rexx@{fg text}  Opens a string requester and passes your
                                input to the IME Server, along with an
                                instruction to find a match for it in
                                the pinyin field of the database

	@{fg shine} find-description.rexx@{fg text}  Opens a string requester and passes your 
                                input to the IME Server, along with an
                                instruction to find a match for it in
                                the English description field of 
                                the database


    To speed up startup, I have also included a variable, 
    which limits how many database entries are loaded, out of the 
    total 26806. This variable @{i}readlines@{ui}, can be found early 
    in imeserver.rexx and is easily altered using any text editor.
    @{fg shine}The default is to read 6000 characters.@{fg text}

    If you want, you could gain another minuscle bit of speed,
    by removing the line that updates the progress gauge while loading...


    More info can be found in the @{" Technical " LINK "Tech"} section.

@EndNode

@Node "Use" "Usage instructions"

  @{b}How to use:@{ub}

    Run one of the input scripts:

	@{fg shine}      find-pinyin.rexx@{fg text}  Lets you look up a character by its
				pinyin transcription. The tones are
				represented by numbers directly
				following the syllables:
				    @{fg shine}1@{fg text} - Flat
				    @{fg shine}2@{fg text} - Rising
				    @{fg shine}3@{fg text} - Falling-Rising
				    @{fg shine}4@{fg text} - Falling
				    @{fg fill}5@{fg text} - @{fg fill}None@{fg text}
				This search does not require complete
				syllables, so "zh" will match Zhong4,
				Zhi1, etc...                              

	@{fg shine} find-description.rexx@{fg text}  Lets you look up a character by searching
				a database of English lanuage descriptions.
				Whole words only.

    You do not need to start the imeserver.rexx script - the first time
    you use one of the input scripts, it will be run.

    Your string will be checked against each database record in turn.

    Once a match has been found, the character will be printed and
    you will be presented with a second requester. Here you can either
    accept the match, by pressing return or the "insert" button, or
    tell the script to keep looking, by pressing the esc key or
    the "next" button. "Cancel" obviously bails you out.

    The database is sorted by frequency of use, so you should not have
    to scan too far, most of the time.


    The find-pinyin.rexx script also contains a list of shortcuts 
    for a few common characters. If you enter one of these, they will
    be entered into the text right away, skipping the lookup stage.

    These shorthands are currently in - add/alter to taste:


	@{fg shine} .@{fg text} - Full stop	(ring)
	@{fg shine} 0@{fg text} - Ling2
	@{fg shine} 1@{fg text} - Yi1
	@{fg shine} 2@{fg text} - Er4
	@{fg shine}22@{fg text} - Liang3
	@{fg shine} 3@{fg text} - San1
	@{fg shine} 4@{fg text} - Si4
	@{fg shine} 5@{fg text} - Wu3
	@{fg shine} 6@{fg text} - Liu4
	@{fg shine} 7@{fg text} - Qi1
	@{fg shine} 8@{fg text} - Ba1
	@{fg shine} 9@{fg text} - Jiu3
	@{fg shine} +@{fg text} - Shi2	(10)
	@{fg shine}++@{fg text} - Bai3	(100)
	@{fg shine} *@{fg text} - Qian1	(1000)
	@{fg shine}**@{fg text} - Wan4	(10000)
	@{fg shine} w@{fg text} - Wo3
	@{fg shine} n@{fg text} - Ni3
	@{fg shine} r@{fg text} - Ren2
	@{fg shine} m@{fg text} - Men
	@{fg shine} s@{fg text} - Shi4
	@{fg shine} b@{fg text} - Bu4
	@{fg shine} g@{fg text} - Ge4
	@{fg shine} d@{fg text} - De
	@{fg shine} h@{fg text} - Hao3
	@{fg shine} y@{fg text} - Ye3
	@{fg shine} ?@{fg text} - Ma
		
@EndNode

@Node "Tech" "Technical info"

  @{b}How the thing is put together:@{ub}

    The data in the database.txt file has been extracted from the 
    Unihan.txt database, which is available by FTP from unicode.org,
    either as-is: @{fg shine}http://www.unicode.org/Public/UNIDATA/Unihan.txt@{fg text}
    ...or zipped: @{fg shine}http://www.unicode.org/Public/UNIDATA/Unihan.zip@{fg text}

    Since it's a 25MB download, I would suggest going for the latter.

    After being gutted of all fields except: @{fg shine}kMandarin, kDefinition,
    kFrequency & kFenn@{fg text}, the database was sorted:

	· First comes all records that have the kFrequency field,
	  which to quote Unihan.txt provides: "@{fg fill}A rough frequency
	  measurement for the character based on analysis of Chinese
	  USENET postings@{fg text}"
	  These records are sorted by their frequency level and within 
	  each level remain in the order they appear in Unhan.txt

	· Second we have the same thing with those 
	  records that have kFenn data. These are very few.

	· Following comes the remainder of the database, unaltered.


    The finished product is a flat LF-delimited database with three
    obligatory fields per record - easy to read with the arexx READLN()
    function and insert into stem variables for Unicode, Transcription
    and Description respectively.

    There is a variable - readlines - which holds the number of
    records to read from the database. The default 6000 includes all
    the records with kFrequency data and should be enough most of the
    time. Just change it to suit your needs.

    Imeserver takes on a rather unelegant start-from-the-beginning-
    and-check-each-record-until-you-reach-the-end brute force approach
    to searching the database, but that's mainly down to the author's
    ineptitude and general lazyness. Feel free to improve.

    Pagestream itself is used for the GUI bit; 
    character display in the active document and 
    its arexx requesters for the interactive bit.
    Only one character is presented at a time and that is simply
    inserted where the cursor is and removed if you decide not to
    use it - this was of course done for the sake of simplicity.

    If you want to access the imeserver once it's running, the port
    is 'IMESERVER', just send "py <string>" for a pinyin search,
    "desc <string>" for a dictionary search in English or 
    "CLOSE" to shut down.

@EndNode

